2669<div>

2670<h1>

2671Finding the Best Kitchen Cabinet Style for Your Kitchen</h1>

2672

2673

2674<p>

2675Buying kitchen cabinets online with Vevano is as simple as selecting your color, style, and budget. With many different cabinet styles and colors, Vevano carries classic, farmhouse, and modern kitchen cabinets. We have the cabinets for your dream kitchen.</p>

2676

2677

2678<p>

2679Whether you&rsquo;re looking for inspiration or ready to start remodeling your home, we have a variety of styles and inspiration guides to help you find cabinets to fit your personal aesthetic. Some of the best styles and colors to get started with are:</p>

2680

2681

2682<h2>

2683Kitchen Cabinet Styles</h2>

2684

2685

2686<ul>

2687

2688 <li>

2689Modern</li>

2690

2691 <li>

2692Transitional</li>

2693

2694 <li>

2695Farmhouse</li>

2696

2697 <li>

2698Classic</li>

2699

2700 <li>

2701Industrial</li>

2702

2703 <li>

2704Cottage</li>

2705

2706 <li>

2707White/Antique White</li>

2708

2709 <li>

2710Grey</li>

2711

2712 <li>

2713Wood</li>

2714

2715 <li>

2716Dark</li>

2717

2718</ul>

2719

2720

2721<p>

2722<br />

2723

2724Updating your kitchen cabinets makes a huge difference in the quality of your home. Mix colors and styles to create a comfortable kitchen your family and friends love.</p>

2725

2726

2727<h3>

2728Modern Kitchen Cabinets</h3>

2729

2730

2731<p>

2732<a href="https://vevano.com/page/modern-kitchen-cabinets/">

2733Modern kitchen cabinet</a>

2734 doors are unembellished with sharp, straight lines. Instead of decorative details, modern cabinets generally have slab style drawers and doors without recessed or raised panels. Many of the cabinets from our Wilora Paloma frameless collections work well in modern kitchens, especially the Monte Carlo Gloss White and Marquis Dark Wood.</p>

2735

2736

2737<p>

2738Look for cabinets in neutral colors such as white, grey, or dark wood. For Mid-Century modern cabinets, you want to imbue warmth and simplicity, so a natural medium-toned wood is ideal. Waterfall countertops or stainless-steel appliances complement modern cabinets well.</p>

2739

2740

2741<ul>

2742

2743 <li>

2744Colors: Neutrals</li>

2745

2746 <li>

2747Door Frames: Slab style</li>

2748

2749 <li>

2750Hardware: Handles in dark metals</li>

2751

2752</ul>

2753

2754

2755<h3>

2756<br />

2757

2758Transitional Kitchen Cabinets</h3>

2759

2760

2761<p>

2762<a href="https://vevano.com/page/transitional-kitchen-cabinets/">

2763Transitional kitchen cabinets</a>

2764 blend classic and modern styles into one cohesive design, but there are multiple ways to achieve this look. Combine a modern slab door with classic metal hardware. Go with a Shaker style door and modern pull hardware. Pair traditional cabinets with modern sinks and contemporary faucets. If you&rsquo;re mixing elements of different styles together, you&rsquo;re achieving a transitional style.</p>

2765

2766

2767<p>

2768The Wilora Hawthorne Eastland cabinet collection is an excellent choice for a transitional kitchen. Its raised panel, beveled door has a classic style that combines perfectly with either curved or straight modern hardware.</p>

2769

2770

2771<p>

2772Color is not associated with a transitional kitchen, so you can play with white, grey, or wood cabinets. Transitional white kitchens are bright and airy, whereas dark transitional cabinets are richly textured and dynamic.</p>

2773

2774

2775<p>

2776Transitional cabinet styles are clean, uncluttered, and purposeful. While transitional is a harder kitchen design to master, the chance to create a unique style adds excitement and interest to your home.</p>

2777

2778

2779<ul>

2780

2781 <li>

2782Colors: Any traditional or neutral colors in white, grey, or dark tones</li>

2783

2784 <li>

2785Door Frames: Modern or classic door frames, often with raised panels</li>

2786

2787 <li>

2788Hardware: Curved or straight edge pulls and knobs</li>

2789

2790 <li>

2791Molding and Panels: Match cabinetry in style</li>

2792

2793</ul>

2794

2795

2796<h3>

2797<br />

2798

2799Farmhouse Kitchen Cabinets</h3>

2800

2801

2802<p>

2803Farmhouse style is all about functional comfort, spacious sinks, light colors, and functional use of space. Decorative details, such as beadboard panels and natural wood, on the island lend a Farmhouse vibe. Farmhouse blends vintage details with modern details for a clean, fresh look.</p>

2804

2805

2806<p>

2807Shaker style works well for <a href="https://vevano.com/page/farmhouse-kitchen-cabinets/">

2808farmhouse kitchen cabinets</a>

2809, as they&rsquo;re practical. The Shaker style features a plain, rectangular frame without beveled edges, and a recessed center panel. The Wilora Hawthorne Cobbleridge White, Shaker White, or the Shaker Dove cabinet collections are ideal for adding Farmhouse flair to your new kitchen.</p>

2810

2811

2812<ul>

2813

2814 <li>

2815Colors: White, light or creamy neutrals</li>

2816

2817 <li>

2818Door Frames: Shaker or recessed</li>

2819

2820 <li>

2821Hardware: Dark metals such as black, brushed nickel, or oil rubbed bronze</li>

2822

2823 <li>

2824Molding and Panels: Plain paneling on cabinets, decorative on islands</li>

2825

2826</ul>

2827

2828

2829<h3>

2830<br />

2831

2832Classic Kitchen Cabinets</h3>

2833

2834

2835<p>

2836The classic style focuses on traditionally timeless cabinets, d&eacute;cor, and colors. Natural wood tones complemented by clean neutral colors are common with the classic style. <a href="https://vevano.com/page/classic-kitchen-cabinets/">

2837Classic kitchen cabinets</a>

2838 generally have raised panel drawers and doors with decorative beveling. Add hardware finishes like brass, polished nickel, or oil-rubbed bronze for a comfortable, antique aesthetic.</p>

2839

2840

2841<p>

2842Design elements are symmetrical, without the sharp contrasts of modern styles. To do this, keep the color palette consistent. Rather than the stark contrast of black and white, opt for white and cream or grey and off-white for counters and cabinets.</p>

2843

2844

2845<ul>

2846

2847 <li>

2848Colors: Creams, off whites, white, and traditional wood tones</li>

2849

2850 <li>

2851Door Frames: Decorative, raised panels</li>

2852

2853 <li>

2854Hardware: Pulls and knobs in antique finishes</li>

2855

2856 <li>

2857Molding and Panels: Decorative end panels, decorative crown molding</li>

2858

2859</ul>

2860

2861

2862<h3>

2863<br />

2864

2865Industrial Kitchen Cabinets</h3>

2866

2867

2868<p>

2869When old warehouses were repurposed for housing and offices, the industrial style craze was born. By keeping old, raw materials, like exposed brick, pipes, and ducts, the style has a unique appeal. You can create an industrial style kitchen even if you don&rsquo;t live in a loft space with brick walls and cast-iron pipes. Go for slab style door frames, large islands, and open wall shelves. A surefire option is to keep your <a href="https://vevano.com/page/industrial-kitchen-cabinets/">

2870industrial kitchen cabinet</a>

2871 color palette monochrome, with light or medium wood, or grey tones. Our Wilora Hawthorne Shaker cabinet collection in Grey, is a good fit for industrial kitchen spaces.</p>

2872

2873

2874<p>

2875Hardware is key in an industrial style kitchen. Wrought iron, steel, or other raw, dark metals fit the style well. Lighting is another way to play up the industrial style, select fixtures with glass or iron features and exposed bulbs.</p>

2876

2877

2878<ul>

2879

2880 <li>

2881Colors: Grey, wood, or monochromatic color schemes</li>

2882

2883 <li>

2997Wood Kitchen Cabinets</h3>

2998

2999

3000<p>

3001Wood has long been the premium material for kitchen cabinets, and it&rsquo;s easy to see why &ndash; the wood grain adds a natural and unique element to your kitchen. No two pieces of wood are the same. From muted tones to vivid multi-colored woodgrains, the comfortable texture of natural wood works well with any style kitchen, from modern to classic to farmhouse. Vevano carries primarily engineered wood, which is less expensive than real hardwood, with many of the same benefits.</p>

3002

3003

3004<p>

3005Most wood cabinets are stained to highlight the unique contours of wood grain. A light stain provides a striking contrast with other elements in your kitchen while a darker stain brings out the contrast of the wood grain, providing dimension.</p>

3006

3007

3008<p>

3009You can paint a wood cabinet, but we don&rsquo;t recommend it unless you&rsquo;re refinishing your existing cabinets. Refinishing your wood cabinets with a coating of paint is an excellent way of getting a new cabinet look without the cost of replacing your cabinets, as all you need to do is sand the surface and paint the cabinets the color of your choice. However, if you&rsquo;re replacing your cabinets and you don&rsquo;t want a stained look, we recommend choosing cabinets made of HDF (high-density fiberboard) over wood. HDF is the better option for paint because it holds an even coat of paint more consistently than wood and doesn&rsquo;t warp.</p>

3065<h2>

3066<br />

3067

3068What are Kitchen Cabinets Made Of?</h2>

3069

3070

3071<p>

3072Whether you choose to go with framed or frameless cabinets, the various components are made from different materials. At Vevano, our cabinets are durable and have plenty of character.</p>

3073

3074

3075<p>

3076<strong>

3077Box Material</strong>

3078</p>

3079

3080

3081<p>

3082The storage area is the cabinet box. Some manufacturers use particleboard because it&rsquo;s an affordable material. However, particleboard isn&rsquo;t made to last and tends to sag and warp under the weight of heavy dishes and marble countertops. As such, we use plywood because it&rsquo;s durable, sturdy, and lasts much longer.</p>

3083

3084

3085<p>

3086Our framed cabinets use plywood boards with a UV-coated wood-veneered interior. Every time you open your cabinets, you show off a natural woodgrain finish, adding to the overall style.</p>

3087

3088

3089<p>

3090Our frameless cabinets use plywood with a white-grey linen interior infused with a durable thermofused melamine surface.</p>

3091

3092

3093<p>

3094<strong>

3095Framed Door Materials</strong>

3096</p>

3097

3098

3099<p>

3100With shaker, raised, or recessed cabinets in our framed cabinet collections, the door and drawer fronts are made of five pieces &ndash; a four-piece frame with a center panel.</p>

3101

3102

3103<p>

3104For stained cabinets, the four-piece frame is made of solid birch with a veneered MDF (medium-density fiberboard) center panel. However, our Wilora Hawthorne Wildwood Saddle cabinets are made entirely of solid birch.</p>

3105

3106

3107<p>

3108For painted cabinets, the frame and center panel are made of HDF (high-density fiberboard) for stability and durability. Since HDF doesn&rsquo;t expand and contract like wood, it&rsquo;s ideal for a framed door because the seams aren&rsquo;t as likely to separate.</p>

3109

3110

3111<p>

3112<strong>

3113Frameless Door Material</strong>

3114</p>

3115

3116

3117<p>

3118The frameless doors in the Wilora Paloma collection are made from engineered wood with textured melamine surfaces. The single-piece slab style doors are great for engineered wood as the wood is free to expand or contract without fear of separating seams.</p>

3119

3120

3121<h3>

3122<br />

3123

3124Pros and Cons of Kitchen Cabinet Materials</h3>

3125

3126

3127<p>

3128<strong>

3129Solid Birch &ndash; </strong>

3130a solid board harvested from a birch tree. Commonly used for cabinets and furniture because it&rsquo;s widely available and durable.</p>

3131

3132

3133<p>

3134Pros:</p>

3135

3136

3137<ul>

3138

3139 <li>

3140Real wood with unique grain patterns</li>

3141

3142 <li>

3143Easy to stain</li>

3144

3145 <li>

3146Can be refinished</li>

3147

3148</ul>

3149

3150

3151<p>

3152Cons:</p>

3153

3154

3155<ul>

3156

3157 <li>

3158Expands and contracts with moisture and humidity</li>

3159

3160 <li>

3161More expensive than engineered wood or fiberboard</li>

3162

3163 <li>

3164Susceptible to bug infestation and rot</li>

3165

3166</ul>

3167

3168

3169<p>

3170<br />

3171

3172<strong>

3173Engineered Wood with a Thermofused Melamine Surface &ndash; </strong>

3174a slab made of several layers of sliced wood glued and pressed together with heat to create a board with a wood-grain textured surface.</p>

3175

3176

3177<p>

3178Pros:</p>

3179

3180

3181<ul>

3182

3183 <li>

3184More affordable than solid wood</li>

3185

3186 <li>

3187Doesn&rsquo;t expand and warp to changes in humidity</li>

3188

3189</ul>

3190

3191

3192<p>

3193Cons:</p>

3194

3195

3196<ul>

3197

3198 <li>

3199Lower quality wood material</li>

3200

3201 <li>

3202Can&rsquo;t be refinished</li>

3203

3204 <li>

3205Uses potentially harmful adhesives</li>

3206

3207</ul>

3208

3209

3210<p>

3211<br />

3212

3213<strong>

3214HDF (high-density fiberboard) &ndash; </strong>

3215a board made of wood fibers mixed with glues and resins and pressed together under pressure to create a dense material used for cabinet panels.</p>

3216

3217

3218<p>

3219Pros:</p>

3220

3221

3222<ul>

3223

3224 <li>

3225Takes a consistent coat of paint very well</li>

3226

3227 <li>

3228Extremely hard</li>

3229

3230 <li>

3231Stable in humid and dry environments</li>

3232

3233</ul>

3234

3235

3236<p>

3237Cons:</p>

3238

3239

3240<ul>

3241

3242 <li>

3243Doesn&rsquo;t have a wood grain</li>

3244

3245 <li>

3246Warps and swells when exposed to water</li>

3247

3248 <li>

3249Lacks the lifespan of wood</li>

3250

3251</ul>

3252

3253

3254<p>

3255<br />

3256

3257<strong>

3258MDF (medium-density fiberboard) &ndash; </strong>

3259a board made in similar fashion to HDF, but without as much pressure, making it lighter and less dense. Used primarily for panels.</p>

3260

3261

3262<p>

3263Pros:</p>

3264

3265

3266<ul>

3267

3268 <li>

3269Easy to paint</li>

3270

3271 <li>

3272Lightweight</li>

3273

3274 <li>

3275Affordable</li>

3276

3277</ul>

3278

3279

3280<p>

3281Cons:</p>

3282

3283

3284<ul>

3285

3286 <li>

3287Not as durable as HDF</li>

3288

3289 <li>

3290Warps and swells when wet</li>

3291

3292 <li>

3293Short shelf life in comparison to other materials</li>

3294

3295</ul>

3296

3297

3298<p>

3299<br />

3300

3301<strong>

3302Plywood &ndash; </strong>

3303thinly sliced sheets of wood glued and pressed together while alternating woodgrain direction 90 degrees. Used for cabinet boxes, shelves, and drawer floors.</p>

3304

3305

3306<p>

3307Pros:</p>

3308

3309

3310<ul>

3311

3312 <li>

3313Doesn&rsquo;t warp or swell in high humidity</li>

3314

3315 <li>

3316Stable and strong enough hold heavy items</li>

3317

3318 <li>

3319Takes a veneer, making it easy to get a beautiful wood look without the cost</li>

3320

3321</ul>

3322

3323

3324<p>

3325Cons:</p>

3326

3327

3328<ul>

3329

3330 <li>

3331More expensive than other engineered materials</li>

3332

3333 <li>

3334Not as strong as solid wood</li>

3335

3336 <li>

3337Low-quality plywood comes apart too easily</li>

3338

3339</ul>

3340

3341

3342<p>

3343<br />

3344

3345<strong>

3346Particleboard &ndash;</strong>

3347 a board made of sawdust, wood chips, synthetic resins and glues pressed together under heat.</p>

3348

3349

3350<p>

3351Pros:</p>

3352

3353

3354<ul>

3355

3356 <li>

3357Extremely budget friendly</li>

3358

3359 <li>

3360Lightweight and great for drawer boxes</li>

3361

3362 <li>

3363Uses wood by-product and recycled materials</li>

3364

3365</ul>

3366

3367

3368<p>

3369Cons:</p>

3370

3371

3372<ul>

3373

3374 <li>

3375Least durable wood product for cabinetry</li>

3376

3377 <li>

3378Sags under heavy dishes, countertops, or appliances</li>

3379

3380 <li>

3381Easily chipped or broken</li>

3383</ul>

3385

3386<h2>

3387<br />

3388

3389How to Install Kitchen Cabinets</h2>

3390

3391

3392<p>

3393Hiring a professional to install your kitchen cabinets is costly. You can expect to pay between $150 to $500 per cabinet or $150 to $350 per square foot. However, you don&rsquo;t have to spend anything. While installing cabinets takes time and sweat, it isn&rsquo;t overly complicated. With the right equipment, precise measurements, and a little confidence you can install your own kitchen cabinets.</p>

3394

3395

3396<ol>

3397

3398 <li>

3399Take very detailed measurements of your kitchen.</li>

3400

3401 <li>

3402Find and mark wall studs with a pencil or chalk.</li>

3403

3404 <li>

3405Mark lines to indicate where the top base cabinets will go. Typically, the top of the base cabinet is 34 &frac12;&rdquo; above the floor, but it can vary with desk base cabinets.</li>

3406

3407 <li>

3408Mark another line at about 53 7/8&rdquo; above the floor to indicate where the bottom of the wall cabinets will be.</li>

3409

3410 <li>

3411Finally, mark a top line to indicate the top of the cabinets at between 83 7/8&rdquo; &ndash; 95 7/8&rdquo; (depending on the height of your wall cabinets). (Check the design plan you received from your designer for specific measurements and a more detailed install guide.)</li>

3412

3413 <li>

3414Starting with your corner wall cabinet box (without the door), use a power drill and a screw (never a nail) to secure the box to the wall by drilling through the cabinet&rsquo;s back panel and into the studs. Make sure to do this at the top and bottom of the cabinet. Drill into two studs where possible. (Reference your design plan for measurements, especially for blind corner cabinets, which need a few inches of space between side walls.)</li>

3415

3416 <li>

3417When installing the next wall cabinet, attach the side adjacent to the mounted cabinet by clamping the sides together and screwing the two cabinet sides together.</li>

3418

3419 <li>

3420Next, install base cabinets by starting with the corner cabinet, referring to your design packet for specific measurements.</li>

3421

3422 <li>

3423Repeat steps 6 and 7, secure the base cabinet to the wall studs and adjacent cabinets.</li>

3424

3425</ol>

3426

3427

3428<p>

3429Want to install your own kitchen cabinets? Contact our design team for a custom design plan. If you&rsquo;re hesitant about installing your own cabinets, we recommend hiring a professional installer.</p>

3430

3431

3432<h2>

3433<br />

3434

3435Can I Paint Kitchen Cabinets?</h2>

3436

3437

3438<p>

3439Yes, painting cabinets is a budget-friendly way to change the look and style of a kitchen without the cost of replacing everything. However, DIY kitchen cabinet painting is time-consuming and can get complex. The current state of your existing cabinets influences how easy your project will be.</p>

3440

3441

3442<p>

3443For example, the surfaces of engineered wood, MDF, or HDF cabinets can&rsquo;t be refinished and prepped for a new coat of paint. They require you to paint over the old color, which may not take the new paint as consistently, causing pooled areas, dripping, and inconsistent streaking.</p>

3444

3445

3446<p>

3447Solid wood cabinets, however, are easy to sand and prime for a smoother painting surface. But prepping the surface is a lot of time-consuming, physical work. If the surface is painted, you need to remove the paint and sand the surface. If the surface is stained, you need to sand the surface until the stain is gone.</p>

3448

3449

3450<p>

3451If you&rsquo;re looking for an easier solution to painting your cabinets, talk to one of our designers for free about a budget solution to update your kitchen. Vevano carries a wide variety of cabinet paint colors and stain styles.</p>

3452

3453

3454<h2>

3455<br />

3456

3457Choosing the Perfect Kitchen Cabinet Hardware and Accessories</h2>

3458

3459

3460<p>

3461Changing up your kitchen accessories is a budget-friendly way to add style and function. Hardware is easy to update with changing styles and adds character to your cabinets. You can also use molding and cabinet lighting to give your cabinets a new look.</p>

3462

3463

3464<p>

3465<strong>

3466Kitchen Cabinet Hardware</strong>

3467</p>

3468

3469

3470<p>

3471Pulls and knobs cap off the style you&rsquo;re searching for while also providing functionality to your doors and drawers. The style of a pull helps determine if a shaker cabinet is either modern, classic, or farmhouse.</p>

3472

3473

3474<p>

3475Knobs are smaller than pulls, typically designed for the fingertips. They come in a variety of sizes, shapes, materials, and finishes. Glass, crystal, metal, or ceramic knobs are all options, depending on the style you&rsquo;re looking for. Shapes are most often round or square but can be oval, geometric, birdcage, abstract, or more.</p>

3476

3477

3478<p>

3479Pulls, on the other hand, are made to fit into your hand, providing greater leverage when opening and closing. This makes pulls ideal for heavy drawers and large doors.</p>

3480

3481

3482<p>

3483Drawer pulls are usually longer than knobs. And while the shape is different, the materials, styles, and finishes are typically the same as knobs. In fact, most pulls have knobs in the same style, allowing you to easily mix and match pulls and knobs in your kitchen without having styles clash.</p>

3484

3485

3486<p>

3487<strong>

3488Kitchen Cabinet Lights</strong>

3489</p>

3490

3491

3492<p>

3493Add functionality and ambiance with under-cabinet and in-cabinet lights. Under-cabinet lighting is a strip of lights or a puck installed to the underside of wall cabinets, illuminating the wall and countertop. This helps with food preparation, cooking, and cleaning. It also brightens up the kitchen since the areas under wall cabinets are generally shadowy and dark. If you have glass-front cabinets, adding in-cabinet lights creates a sophisticated look, like museum display cases, to highlight your favorite decorative dishware. They also make finding what you want easy and fast.</p>

3494

3495

3496<p>

3497<strong>

3498Kitchen Cabinet Molding</strong>

3499</p>

3500

3501

3502<p>

3503Added to the tops and bottoms of cabinets, molding adds a bit of panache and helps make your cabinets look complete and cohesive. Here are some different types of molding:</p>

3504

3505

3506<ul>

3507

3508 <li>

3509<em>

3510Crown molding</em>

3511 encapsulates many types of molding, but it&rsquo;s a decorative piece installed to the top of the wall cabinets, either to make the cabinets look taller or create a decorative transition between the cabinets and the ceiling.</li>

3512

3513 <li>

3514<em>

3515Angle Crown Molding </em>

3516is a decorative piece placed between the bottom of the wall cabinet and the wall, creating a nice angled transition from the cabinet to the wall.</li>

3517

3518 <li>

3519<em>

3520Light rail molding</em>

3521 goes on the outside bottom of wall cabinets, adding decorative edges while concealing under-cabinet lights.</li>

3522

3523 <li>

3524<em>

3525Toe-kick molding</em>

3526 covers the space between the cabinets and the floor.</li>

3527

3528 <li>

3529<em>

3530Scribe Molding </em>

3531is a small piece of wood used to cover inconsistencies, such as small gaps between two cabinets or where a cabinet meets a wall.</li>

3532

3533 <li>

3534<em>

3535Shoe Molding </em>

3536is a rounded piece of wood used to cover inconsistencies between the toe-kick molding and the floor or the wall and the floor.</li>

3537

3538 <li>

3539<em>

3540Apron Molding </em>

3541is a decorative piece of wood used as trim on the underside of wall cabinets or for windows near the cabinets. It&rsquo;s used to conceal joints.</li>

3542

3543 <li>

3544<em>

3545Batten Molding </em>

3546is a thin strip of wood used to cover seams between panels or cabinets.</li>

3547

3548 <li>

3549<em>

3550Rope Molding </em>

3551is a decorative piece of wood carved to look like rope. It&rsquo;s used to cover seams or add decorative details.</li>

3552

3553</ul>

3554

3555

3556<p>

3557<br />

3558

3559<strong>

3560Kitchen Cabinet Panels</strong>

3561</p>

3562

3563

3564<p>

3565Kitchen cabinet panels are affixed to the exposed sides of cabinets, islands, and appliances to cover the exposed, unfinished sides of a cabinet box. Panels are available in decorative end panels, refrigerator end panels, dishwasher panels, and more. Designed to &ldquo;finish&rdquo; unfinished cabinets, panels are necessary to ensure a consistent look throughout your cabinets.</p>

3566

3567

3568<h2>

3569<br />

3570

3571How to Organize Kitchen Cabinets</h2>

3572

3573

3574<p>

3575With so many styles, configurations, and options available, it&rsquo;s easy to customize <a href="https://vevano.com/catalog/cabinets-organization/">

3576your cabinet organization</a>

3577 to your lifestyle. Organization is key to making your cabinet storage practical.</p>

3578

3579

3580<p>

3581<strong>

3582Shelves</strong>

3583</p>

3584

3585

3586<p>

3587While most cabinets come with shelving, there are many additional <a href="https://vevano.com/catalog/cabinets-kitchen-parts-and-accessories/">

3588cabinet parts</a>

3589 for making your life easier.</p>

3590

3591

3592<ul>

3593

3594 <li>

3595Shelf organizers for pots, pans, and their matching lids.</li>

3596

3597 <li>

3598Floating shelves for your most used items (bowls, mugs, etc.), on eye-level shelves.</li>

3599

3600 <li>

3601Rollout shelves as a terrific alternative to traditional shelves, making it easier to access large items.</li>

3602

3603 <li>

3604Pulldown shelves for accessing high items, so you don&rsquo;t need a step ladder and can access items safely.</li>

3605

3606</ul>

3607

3608

3609<p>

3610<br />

3611

3612<strong>

3613Lazy Susans</strong>

3614</p>

3615

3616

3617<p>

3618A Lazy Susan is a swiveling shelf ideal for corner cabinets where accessing the space is awkward and difficult. Perfect for containers, pots and pans, Tupperware, or snacks, a Lazy Susan provides an easier way to reach for kitchen necessities because you can turn the Lazy Susan, bringing the items to the front.</p>

3619

3620

3621<p>

3622When storing containers on Lazy Susans, store lids with them or on the same shelf. These shelves are also great for storing snacks like crackers, canned food, or healthy afterschool treats.</p>

3623

3624

3625<p>

3626<strong>

3627Drawers</strong>

3628</p>

3629

3630

3631<p>

3632Drawer organizers provide a great solution for safely storing utensils, flatware, and dishware. Large drawers are designed to accommodate stacked plates, food storage containers, mixing bowls, and more to keep your countertops free from clutter.</p>

3633

3634

3635<p>

3636Store cooking utensils in drawers by type of cooking, for easy access. Drawers close to the stove are perfect for oven gloves or pot-stirring spoons. Island drawers are great for flatware, close to seating or dining areas.</p>

3637

3638

3639<p>

3640<strong>

3641Spice Racks</strong>

3642</p>

3643

3644

3645<p>

3646Keep herbs and spices arranged neatly with a spice rack. Vevano carries a variety of spice rack organizers. Choose a door-mounted spice rack for upper shelves to keep your spice shakers at eye-level. Pick a drawer organizer spice rack to easily customize any drawer and keep your spices within reach. Vevano also carries spice rack base cabinets &ndash; slim 6&rdquo; cabinets with rollout drawers to store spices.</p>

3647

3648

3649<p>

3650<strong>

3651Trash Can Pull-Outs</strong>

3652</p>

3653

3654

3655<p>

3656Maximize your storage space with a pull-out trash can. Many pull-outs also work for recycling and compost bins, or for storing cleaning supplies. A pull-out trash can also free up floor space in your kitchen and keeps trash out of reach from pets and children.</p>

3657

3658

3659<h2>

3660<br />

3661

3662FAQs About Kitchen Cabinets</h2>

3663

3664

3665<p>

3666Do you have a question about your kitchen cabinet remodel? Don&rsquo;t see your question below? Contact our design team at <a href="mailto:design@vevano.com">

3667design@vevano.com</a>

3668 to get your questions answered.</p>

3669

3670

3671<h3>

3672What color cabinets make a kitchen look bigger?</h3>

3673

3674

3675<p>

3676Light colors are best for making kitchens feel bigger because they reflect light, making rooms feel brighter, airy, and more spacious. White is the most reflective but colors like cream and light greys also reflect more light than darker colors.</p>

3677

3678

3679<p>

3680Check out our <a href="https://vevano.com/page/white-kitchen-cabinet-collections/">

3681white kitchen cabinet collections</a>

3682 for a bright kitchen, or our <a href="https://vevano.com/page/gray-kitchen-cabinet-collections/">

3683grey kitchen cabinet collections</a>

3684 for a slightly warmer kitchen.</p>

3685

3686

3687<h3>

3688What is the best height for kitchen cabinets?</h3>

3689

3690

3691<p>

3692The standard height for base cabinets is 34 &frac12;&rdquo; (without countertops). The bottom of your wall cabinets should be about 54&rdquo; above the floor. These measurements leave enough space between your wall cabinets and your counter for appliances and cooking space. Wall cabinets themselves are typically between 30&rdquo; and 42&rdquo; high, depending on the design of your kitchen, the cabinet style, and height of your ceiling.</p>

3693

3694

3695<h3>

3696When do you need a cabinet contractor?</h3>

3697

3698

3699<p>

3700Hire a cabinet contractor when you&rsquo;re ready in start your kitchen remodel. Whether you book an installer before you order cabinets or after, have them contact us at Vevano Pro. We work with your contractor throughout the shipping, assembly, and installation process to ensure your overall satisfaction.</p>

3701

3702

3703<p>

3704We recommend hiring a cabinet contractor if any of the following apply to you:</p>

3705

3706

3707<ul>

3708

3709 <li>

3710<em>

3711You don&rsquo;t have another person to help you.</em>

3712 Wall cabinets require at least two people to safely and accurately install.</li>

3713

3714 <li>

3715<em>

3716You&rsquo;re unable to lift more than 20 pounds.</em>

3717 Cabinets are large, so leave the heavy lifting to an expert.</li>

3718

3719 <li>

3720<em>

3721You have a time constraint.</em>

3722 Installing cabinets prior to a holiday party or selling your home? Professional installers can complete the project quickly.</li>

3723

3724 <li>

3725<em>

3726Your kitchen&rsquo;s floorplan is complicated.</em>

3727 Professionals know how to better handle an uneven floor, non-standard sizing, and electrical or plumbing issues.</li>

3728

3729</ul>

3730

3731

3732<p>

3733Depending on the size of your kitchen, it usually takes at least 2 to 3 days for a professional to install kitchen cabinets. Give yourself plenty of time if you need your cabinets installed on a deadline.</p>

3734

3735

3736<h3>

3737How much does it cost to replace kitchen cabinets?</h3>

3738

3739

3740<p>

3741The average cost to replace your kitchen cabinets is between $2,000 and $4,000. A general rule is to plan about $100 per linear foot of kitchen. So, if you have a 10 ft wall and another 10 ft wall, that&rsquo;s 20 feet for base cabinets and 20 ft for wall cabinets, or 40 linear feet and $4,000 total.</p>

3742

3743

3744<p>

3745Vevano carries RTA, or ready to assemble cabinets. With these, the cost of replacing cabinets in a 10x10 kitchen is generally between $2,000 and $3,000 for a 10x10 kitchen. We&rsquo;ll send you detailed instructions for you can assemble cabinets yourself or hire a professional installer to do the work for you.</p>

3746

3747

3748<p>

3749Preassembled cabinets are a bit more expensive, as you are paying for the assembly rather than doing it yourself. They also require more storage space so prepare a section of your home or garage to house the cabinets while you wait to install them.</p>

3750

3751

3752<p>

3753Custom cabinets are the most expensive type of cabinetry and can set you back $7,000 to $9,000 (or more) for a 10x10 kitchen. They are best for unique layouts.</p>

3754

3755

3756<h3>

3757How much does it cost to install kitchen cabinets?</h3>

3758

3759

3760<p>

3761<strong>

3762Installing Your Own Cabinets</strong>

3763</p>

3764

3765

3766<p>

3767First, you need tools: a hammer, ladder, miter saw, drill, stud finder, line level, clamps, and more. The average cost for tools to install kitchen cabinets is about $300 to $700. You can also save money by renting tools from your local hardware shop as well.</p>

3768

3769

3770<p>

3771Pros: Save money and learn a new skill.</p>

3772

3773

3774<p>

3775Cons: Installing your own cabinets without prior experience could result in costly mistakes, injury, or damage to your home.</p>

3776

3777

3778<p>

3779<strong>

3780Hiring a Cabinet Installer</strong>

3781</p>

3782

3783

3784<p>

3785For a professional installation, plan on at least $75 per linear foot. Pricing depends on the market in your area, but for a 10x10 kitchen with 40 linear feet, installers charge about $3,000 - $5,000.</p>

3786

3787

3788<p>

3789Pros: Trained contractors work quickly and install with more accuracy. Many installers also remove and dispose of your old kitchen cabinets for you.</p>

3790

3791

3792<p>

3793Cons: Adds significant cost to your renovation.</p>

3794

3795

3796<h3>

3797How many cabinets are in a 10x10 kitchen?</h3>

3798

3799

3800<p>

3801Most 10x10 kitchens usually have 10-12 cabinets: four to five base cabinets and six to seven wall cabinets. Your unique kitchen may require different quantities or types of cabinets. Some products are more common than others, such as sink base cabinets and corner cabinets for both base and wall. A bridge cabinet for over the refrigerator is also a common design element. Less common are desk, oven, and tall cabinets, since 10x10 kitchens are often too small.</p>

3802

3803

3804<h3>

3805Why are kitchen cabinets expensive?</h3>

3806

3807

3808<p>

3809Kitchen cabinets are expensive because they&rsquo;re designed to be an integral part of your home for decades. Quality cabinets are built to last up to fifty years or more. Even though it&rsquo;s easy to change your cabinetry, kitchen cabinets are more permanent than ordinary furniture.</p>

3810

3811

3812<p>

3813Vevano&rsquo;s cabinets are solid, durable, and can add value to your home to recoup some of your original investment. We even carry a few cabinet collections for 10x10 kitchens under $2,000. Contact our design team to receive a kitchen design plan that works with your budget.</p>

They&rsquo;ll help you take measurements of your kitchen, choose the cabinet style, material, and color for your home. Your custom design comes complete with cabinet pieces, an install guide, kitchen cabinet pictures, and general style advice.</p>

3824

3825

3826<p>

3827Just need help choosing cabinet hardware, or organization? Our <a href="https://vevano.com/page/design-services/">

3828room planners</a>

3829 can guide you through accessories too. They can recommend organization solutions for your kitchen&rsquo;s specific measurements or complementary hardware finishes for your existing cabinet colors.</p>

Mix colors and styles to create a comfortable kitchen your family and friends love.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eModern Kitchen Cabinets\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/page/modern-kitchen-cabinets/\"\u003eModern kitchen cabinet\u003c/a\u003e doors are unembellished with sharp, straight lines. Instead of decorative details, modern cabinets generally have slab style drawers and doors without recessed or raised panels. Many of the cabinets from our Wilora Paloma frameless collections work well in modern kitchens, especially the Monte Carlo Gloss White and Marquis Dark Wood.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eLook for cabinets in neutral colors such as white, grey, or dark wood. For Mid-Century modern cabinets, you want to imbue warmth and simplicity, so a natural medium-toned wood is ideal. Waterfall countertops or stainless-steel appliances complement modern cabinets well.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eColors: Neutrals\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eDoor Frames: Slab style\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eHardware: Handles in dark metals\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nTransitional Kitchen Cabinets\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/page/transitional-kitchen-cabinets/\"\u003eTransitional kitchen cabinets\u003c/a\u003e blend classic and modern styles into one cohesive design, but there are multiple ways to achieve this look. Combine a modern slab door with classic metal hardware. Go with a Shaker style door and modern pull hardware. Pair traditional cabinets with modern sinks and contemporary faucets. If you\u0026rsquo;re mixing elements of different styles together, you\u0026rsquo;re achieving a transitional style.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe Wilora Hawthorne Eastland cabinet collection is an excellent choice for a transitional kitchen. Its raised panel, beveled door has a classic style that combines perfectly with either curved or straight modern hardware.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eColor is not associated with a transitional kitchen, so you can play with white, grey, or wood cabinets. Transitional white kitchens are bright and airy, whereas dark transitional cabinets are richly textured and dynamic.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eTransitional cabinet styles are clean, uncluttered, and purposeful. While transitional is a harder kitchen design to master, the chance to create a unique style adds excitement and interest to your home.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eColors: Any traditional or neutral colors in white, grey, or dark tones\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eDoor Frames: Modern or classic door frames, often with raised panels\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eHardware: Curved or straight edge pulls and knobs\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eMolding and Panels: Match cabinetry in style\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nFarmhouse Kitchen Cabinets\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFarmhouse style is all about functional comfort, spacious sinks, light colors, and functional use of space. Decorative details, such as beadboard panels and natural wood, on the island lend a Farmhouse vibe. Farmhouse blends vintage details with modern details for a clean, fresh look.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eShaker style works well for \u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/page/farmhouse-kitchen-cabinets/\"\u003efarmhouse kitchen cabinets\u003c/a\u003e, as they\u0026rsquo;re practical. The Shaker style features a plain, rectangular frame without beveled edges, and a recessed center panel. The Wilora Hawthorne Cobbleridge White, Shaker White, or the Shaker Dove cabinet collections are ideal for adding Farmhouse flair to your new kitchen.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eColors: White, light or creamy neutrals\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eDoor Frames: Shaker or recessed\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eHardware: Dark metals such as black, brushed nickel, or oil rubbed bronze\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eMolding and Panels: Plain paneling on cabinets, decorative on islands\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nClassic Kitchen Cabinets\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe classic style focuses on traditionally timeless cabinets, d\u0026eacute;cor, and colors. Natural wood tones complemented by clean neutral colors are common with the classic style. \u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/page/classic-kitchen-cabinets/\"\u003eClassic kitchen cabinets\u003c/a\u003e generally have raised panel drawers and doors with decorative beveling. Add hardware finishes like brass, polished nickel, or oil-rubbed bronze for a comfortable, antique aesthetic.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eDesign elements are symmetrical, without the sharp contrasts of modern styles. To do this, keep the color palette consistent. Rather than the stark contrast of black and white, opt for white and cream or grey and off-white for counters and cabinets.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eColors: Creams, off whites, white, and traditional wood tones\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eDoor Frames: Decorative, raised panels\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eHardware: Pulls and knobs in antique finishes\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eMolding and Panels: Decorative end panels, decorative crown molding\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nIndustrial Kitchen Cabinets\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWhen old warehouses were repurposed for housing and offices, the industrial style craze was born. By keeping old, raw materials, like exposed brick, pipes, and ducts, the style has a unique appeal. You can create an industrial style kitchen even if you don\u0026rsquo;t live in a loft space with brick walls and cast-iron pipes. Go for slab style door frames, large islands, and open wall shelves. A surefire option is to keep your \u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/page/industrial-kitchen-cabinets/\"\u003eindustrial kitchen cabinet\u003c/a\u003e color palette monochrome, with light or medium wood, or grey tones. Our Wilora Hawthorne Shaker cabinet collection in Grey, is a good fit for industrial kitchen spaces.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eHardware is key in an industrial style kitchen. Wrought iron, steel, or other raw, dark metals fit the style well. Lighting is another way to play up the industrial style, select fixtures with glass or iron features and exposed bulbs.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eColors: Grey, wood, or monochromatic color schemes\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eDoor Frames: Modern, slab, or Shaker style\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eHardware: Iron, steel, and knobs or pulls with black finishes\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eMolding and Panels: Very little molding or decoration, keep panels plain and simple\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nCottage Kitchen Cabinets\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe cottage style is like farmhouse but leans more towards rustic and eclectic elements. Lived-in comfort is a key, so choose inviting colors in white or off-white to give your kitchen a cheerful and open look. For flooring and backsplash, stone tiles match the cottage style while keeping the color palette fresh and natural.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/page/cottage-kitchen-cabinets/\"\u003eCottage kitchen cabinets\u003c/a\u003e are delicate in style, with ornate elements and intricate details, allowing you to be creative with hardware. Select unique designs in antique finishes or polished metal. Our Wilora Hawthrone Cobbleridge Dove cabinet collection fits well with a cottage style kitchen. The decorative beveling on the door and drawer front panels carries a hint of elegance without ostentation.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eColors: Light colors, whites, creams, or off-whites\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eDoor Frames: Beveled frames with raised panels\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eHardware: Antique finishes in charming shapes\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eMolding and Panels: Decorative and ornate\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nWhite and Antique White Kitchen Cabinets\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/page/white-kitchen-cabinet-collections/\"\u003eWhite kitchen cabinets\u003c/a\u003e are among the most popular colors we carry because it\u0026rsquo;s so versatile. White goes with almost every color palette or style, offering a fresh, inviting look to your kitchen. White makes small kitchens look bigger and makes the most of the light you have. Since white is a clean color, it helps your kitchen feel sparkling and orderly, even when it isn\u0026rsquo;t. But this cleanliness does come at a price, as it requires more upkeep than dark cabinets because dirt and grime is more visible.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWe offer a variety of shades and finishes for white cabinets \u0026ndash; glossy white, bright white, or creamy antique white. Vevano carries many white collections in different door styles, such as the classic Wilora Hawthrone Shaker White, the Wilora Paloma Monte Carlo Gloss White for modern kitchens, or the Wilora Hawthorne Cobbleridge White for farmhouse kitchens. Antique white works well in cottage style kitchens as it feels vintage, but adds warmth to the bright, clean aesthetic that white is known for.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eUse hardware to play up different aesthetic appeals, such as straight plain pulls for contemporary designs or playful antique knobs for cottage kitchens.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eColors: White, Gloss White, Antique White, Oyster Shell\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eDoor Panels: Raised or recessed frames, or frameless slab-style\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eHardware: Contrasting finishes such as nickel, black, or brass\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eMolding and Panels: Any\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nGrey Kitchen Cabinets\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/page/gray-kitchen-cabinet-collections/\"\u003eGrey kitchen cabinets\u003c/a\u003e range from dark cinder to light dove. The tone of grey influences how your new kitchen looks and feels. For a cool-toned kitchen, opt for a grey-blue. For a warmer feel, go with a grey red tone.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eMuch like white, grey is versatile, pairing well with other colors, from the pretty contrast of white to the cool complement of navy blue. Grey cabinets are excellent in kitchens with bold colors for flooring, countertops, appliances, and d\u0026eacute;cor. Colors: Grey, Cinder, Dove\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eDoor Frames: Raised or recessed frames, or frameless slab-style\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eHardware: Contrasting metals such as polished nickel, chrome, or black\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eMolding and Panels: Any\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nWood Kitchen Cabinets\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWood has long been the premium material for kitchen cabinets, and it\u0026rsquo;s easy to see why \u0026ndash; the wood grain adds a natural and unique element to your kitchen. No two pieces of wood are the same. From muted tones to vivid multi-colored woodgrains, the comfortable texture of natural wood works well with any style kitchen, from modern to classic to farmhouse. Vevano carries primarily engineered wood, which is less expensive than real hardwood, with many of the same benefits.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eMost wood cabinets are stained to highlight the unique contours of wood grain. A light stain provides a striking contrast with other elements in your kitchen while a darker stain brings out the contrast of the wood grain, providing dimension.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eYou can paint a wood cabinet, but we don\u0026rsquo;t recommend it unless you\u0026rsquo;re refinishing your existing cabinets. Refinishing your wood cabinets with a coating of paint is an excellent way of getting a new cabinet look without the cost of replacing your cabinets, as all you need to do is sand the surface and paint the cabinets the color of your choice. However, if you\u0026rsquo;re replacing your cabinets and you don\u0026rsquo;t want a stained look, we recommend choosing cabinets made of HDF (high-density fiberboard) over wood. HDF is the better option for paint because it holds an even coat of paint more consistently than wood and doesn\u0026rsquo;t warp.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/page/wood-kitchen-cabinet-collections/\"\u003eWood kitchen cabinets\u003c/a\u003e are available in a variety of door frame styles. Beveled wood doors enhance cottage kitchens, adding to a vintage feel. Plain door frames in natural wood add a modern, simple twist but also enriches the rustic feel of farmhouse kitchens.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eColors: Saddle, Chocolate, Conch Shell, Grey Wood, Oyster Shell, Dark Wood\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eDoor Frames: Raised or recessed frames, or frameless slab-style\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eHardware: Dark hardware on light cabinets, or light hardware on dark cabinets\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eMolding and Panels: Any\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nDark Kitchen Cabinets\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWhere lighter hues open a room, darker tones bring an elegance, especially when paired with contrasting light colors for countertops, flooring, appliances, and d\u0026eacute;cor. \u0026nbsp;They are easy to clean, as they hide blemishes and dirt better than white cabinets, but dark colors absorb light, making smaller kitchens feel even smaller.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/page/dark-kitchen-cabinet-collections/\"\u003eDark kitchen cabinets\u003c/a\u003e are available in a wide range of door frame styles, from modern frameless construction to transitional Shaker greys. Our Wilora Hawthorne Shaker Espresso collection feature a natural wood look, with deep, warm tones for classic kitchens. Colors: Cinder, Espresso, dark grey, dark wood\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eDoor Frames: Raised or recessed frames, or frameless slab-style\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eHardware: Contrasting colors and lighter metals like chrome or nickel\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eMolding and Panels: Any\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003ch2\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nWhat are Kitchen Cabinets Made Of?\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWhether you choose to go with framed or frameless cabinets, the various components are made from different materials. At Vevano, our cabinets are durable and have plenty of character.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBox Material\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe storage area is the cabinet box. Some manufacturers use particleboard because it\u0026rsquo;s an affordable material. However, particleboard isn\u0026rsquo;t made to last and tends to sag and warp under the weight of heavy dishes and marble countertops. As such, we use plywood because it\u0026rsquo;s durable, sturdy, and lasts much longer.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eOur framed cabinets use plywood boards with a UV-coated wood-veneered interior. Every time you open your cabinets, you show off a natural woodgrain finish, adding to the overall style.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eOur frameless cabinets use plywood with a white-grey linen interior infused with a durable thermofused melamine surface.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eFramed Door Materials\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWith shaker, raised, or recessed cabinets in our framed cabinet collections, the door and drawer fronts are made of five pieces \u0026ndash; a four-piece frame with a center panel.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFor stained cabinets, the four-piece frame is made of solid birch with a veneered MDF (medium-density fiberboard) center panel. However, our Wilora Hawthorne Wildwood Saddle cabinets are made entirely of solid birch.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFor painted cabinets, the frame and center panel are made of HDF (high-density fiberboard) for stability and durability. Since HDF doesn\u0026rsquo;t expand and contract like wood, it\u0026rsquo;s ideal for a framed door because the seams aren\u0026rsquo;t as likely to separate.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eFrameless Door Material\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe frameless doors in the Wilora Paloma collection are made from engineered wood with textured melamine surfaces. The single-piece slab style doors are great for engineered wood as the wood is free to expand or contract without fear of separating seams.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nPros and Cons of Kitchen Cabinet Materials\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSolid Birch \u0026ndash; \u003c/strong\u003ea solid board harvested from a birch tree. Commonly used for cabinets and furniture because it\u0026rsquo;s widely available and durable.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003ePros:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eReal wood with unique grain patterns\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eEasy to stain\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eCan be refinished\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eCons:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eExpands and contracts with moisture and humidity\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eMore expensive than engineered wood or fiberboard\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eSusceptible to bug infestation and rot\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\n\u003cstrong\u003eEngineered Wood with a Thermofused Melamine Surface \u0026ndash; \u003c/strong\u003ea slab made of several layers of sliced wood glued and pressed together with heat to create a board with a wood-grain textured surface.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003ePros:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eMore affordable than solid wood\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eDoesn\u0026rsquo;t expand and warp to changes in humidity\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eCons:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eLower quality wood material\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eCan\u0026rsquo;t be refinished\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eUses potentially harmful adhesives\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\n\u003cstrong\u003eHDF (high-density fiberboard) \u0026ndash; \u003c/strong\u003ea board made of wood fibers mixed with glues and resins and pressed together under pressure to create a dense material used for cabinet panels.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003ePros:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eTakes a consistent coat of paint very well\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eExtremely hard\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eStable in humid and dry environments\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eCons:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eDoesn\u0026rsquo;t have a wood grain\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eWarps and swells when exposed to water\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eLacks the lifespan of wood\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\n\u003cstrong\u003eMDF (medium-density fiberboard) \u0026ndash; \u003c/strong\u003ea board made in similar fashion to HDF, but without as much pressure, making it lighter and less dense. Used primarily for panels.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003ePros:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eEasy to paint\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eLightweight\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eAffordable\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eCons:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eNot as durable as HDF\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eWarps and swells when wet\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eShort shelf life in comparison to other materials\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\n\u003cstrong\u003ePlywood \u0026ndash; \u003c/strong\u003ethinly sliced sheets of wood glued and pressed together while alternating woodgrain direction 90 degrees. Used for cabinet boxes, shelves, and drawer floors.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003ePros:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eDoesn\u0026rsquo;t warp or swell in high humidity\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eStable and strong enough hold heavy items\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eTakes a veneer, making it easy to get a beautiful wood look without the cost\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eCons:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eMore expensive than other engineered materials\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eNot as strong as solid wood\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eLow-quality plywood comes apart too easily\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\n\u003cstrong\u003eParticleboard \u0026ndash;\u003c/strong\u003e a board made of sawdust, wood chips, synthetic resins and glues pressed together under heat.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003ePros:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eExtremely budget friendly\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eLightweight and great for drawer boxes\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eUses wood by-product and recycled materials\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eCons:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eLeast durable wood product for cabinetry\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eSags under heavy dishes, countertops, or appliances\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eEasily chipped or broken\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003ch2\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nHow to Install Kitchen Cabinets\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eHiring a professional to install your kitchen cabinets is costly. You can expect to pay between $150 to $500 per cabinet or $150 to $350 per square foot. However, you don\u0026rsquo;t have to spend anything. While installing cabinets takes time and sweat, it isn\u0026rsquo;t overly complicated. With the right equipment, precise measurements, and a little confidence you can install your own kitchen cabinets.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003col\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eTake very detailed measurements of your kitchen.\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eFind and mark wall studs with a pencil or chalk.\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eMark lines to indicate where the top base cabinets will go. Typically, the top of the base cabinet is 34 \u0026frac12;\u0026rdquo; above the floor, but it can vary with desk base cabinets.\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eMark another line at about 53 7/8\u0026rdquo; above the floor to indicate where the bottom of the wall cabinets will be.\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eFinally, mark a top line to indicate the top of the cabinets at between 83 7/8\u0026rdquo; \u0026ndash; 95 7/8\u0026rdquo; (depending on the height of your wall cabinets). (Check the design plan you received from your designer for specific measurements and a more detailed install guide.)\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eStarting with your corner wall cabinet box (without the door), use a power drill and a screw (never a nail) to secure the box to the wall by drilling through the cabinet\u0026rsquo;s back panel and into the studs. Make sure to do this at the top and bottom of the cabinet. Drill into two studs where possible. (Reference your design plan for measurements, especially for blind corner cabinets, which need a few inches of space between side walls.)\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eWhen installing the next wall cabinet, attach the side adjacent to the mounted cabinet by clamping the sides together and screwing the two cabinet sides together.\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eNext, install base cabinets by starting with the corner cabinet, referring to your design packet for specific measurements.\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eRepeat steps 6 and 7, secure the base cabinet to the wall studs and adjacent cabinets.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ol\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWant to install your own kitchen cabinets? Contact our design team for a custom design plan. If you\u0026rsquo;re hesitant about installing your own cabinets, we recommend hiring a professional installer.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nCan I Paint Kitchen Cabinets?\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eYes, painting cabinets is a budget-friendly way to change the look and style of a kitchen without the cost of replacing everything. However, DIY kitchen cabinet painting is time-consuming and can get complex. The current state of your existing cabinets influences how easy your project will be.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFor example, the surfaces of engineered wood, MDF, or HDF cabinets can\u0026rsquo;t be refinished and prepped for a new coat of paint. They require you to paint over the old color, which may not take the new paint as consistently, causing pooled areas, dripping, and inconsistent streaking.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eSolid wood cabinets, however, are easy to sand and prime for a smoother painting surface. But prepping the surface is a lot of time-consuming, physical work. If the surface is painted, you need to remove the paint and sand the surface. If the surface is stained, you need to sand the surface until the stain is gone.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eIf you\u0026rsquo;re looking for an easier solution to painting your cabinets, talk to one of our designers for free about a budget solution to update your kitchen. Vevano carries a wide variety of cabinet paint colors and stain styles.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nChoosing the Perfect Kitchen Cabinet Hardware and Accessories\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eChanging up your kitchen accessories is a budget-friendly way to add style and function. Hardware is easy to update with changing styles and adds character to your cabinets. You can also use molding and cabinet lighting to give your cabinets a new look.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eKitchen Cabinet Hardware\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003ePulls and knobs cap off the style you\u0026rsquo;re searching for while also providing functionality to your doors and drawers. The style of a pull helps determine if a shaker cabinet is either modern, classic, or farmhouse.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eKnobs are smaller than pulls, typically designed for the fingertips. They come in a variety of sizes, shapes, materials, and finishes. Glass, crystal, metal, or ceramic knobs are all options, depending on the style you\u0026rsquo;re looking for. Shapes are most often round or square but can be oval, geometric, birdcage, abstract, or more.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003ePulls, on the other hand, are made to fit into your hand, providing greater leverage when opening and closing. This makes pulls ideal for heavy drawers and large doors.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eDrawer pulls are usually longer than knobs. And while the shape is different, the materials, styles, and finishes are typically the same as knobs. In fact, most pulls have knobs in the same style, allowing you to easily mix and match pulls and knobs in your kitchen without having styles clash.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eKitchen Cabinet Lights\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAdd functionality and ambiance with under-cabinet and in-cabinet lights. Under-cabinet lighting is a strip of lights or a puck installed to the underside of wall cabinets, illuminating the wall and countertop. This helps with food preparation, cooking, and cleaning. It also brightens up the kitchen since the areas under wall cabinets are generally shadowy and dark. If you have glass-front cabinets, adding in-cabinet lights creates a sophisticated look, like museum display cases, to highlight your favorite decorative dishware. They also make finding what you want easy and fast.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eKitchen Cabinet Molding\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAdded to the tops and bottoms of cabinets, molding adds a bit of panache and helps make your cabinets look complete and cohesive. Here are some different types of molding:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003e\u003cem\u003eCrown molding\u003c/em\u003e encapsulates many types of molding, but it\u0026rsquo;s a decorative piece installed to the top of the wall cabinets, either to make the cabinets look taller or create a decorative transition between the cabinets and the ceiling.\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003e\u003cem\u003eAngle Crown Molding \u003c/em\u003eis a decorative piece placed between the bottom of the wall cabinet and the wall, creating a nice angled transition from the cabinet to the wall.\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003e\u003cem\u003eLight rail molding\u003c/em\u003e goes on the outside bottom of wall cabinets, adding decorative edges while concealing under-cabinet lights.\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003e\u003cem\u003eToe-kick molding\u003c/em\u003e covers the space between the cabinets and the floor.\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003e\u003cem\u003eScribe Molding \u003c/em\u003eis a small piece of wood used to cover inconsistencies, such as small gaps between two cabinets or where a cabinet meets a wall.\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003e\u003cem\u003eShoe Molding \u003c/em\u003eis a rounded piece of wood used to cover inconsistencies between the toe-kick molding and the floor or the wall and the floor.\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003e\u003cem\u003eApron Molding \u003c/em\u003eis a decorative piece of wood used as trim on the underside of wall cabinets or for windows near the cabinets. It\u0026rsquo;s used to conceal joints.\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003e\u003cem\u003eBatten Molding \u003c/em\u003eis a thin strip of wood used to cover seams between panels or cabinets.\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003e\u003cem\u003eRope Molding \u003c/em\u003eis a decorative piece of wood carved to look like rope. It\u0026rsquo;s used to cover seams or add decorative details.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\n\u003cstrong\u003eKitchen Cabinet Panels\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eKitchen cabinet panels are affixed to the exposed sides of cabinets, islands, and appliances to cover the exposed, unfinished sides of a cabinet box. Panels are available in decorative end panels, refrigerator end panels, dishwasher panels, and more. Designed to \u0026ldquo;finish\u0026rdquo; unfinished cabinets, panels are necessary to ensure a consistent look throughout your cabinets.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nHow to Organize Kitchen Cabinets\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWith so many styles, configurations, and options available, it\u0026rsquo;s easy to customize \u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/catalog/cabinets-organization/\"\u003eyour cabinet organization\u003c/a\u003e to your lifestyle. Organization is key to making your cabinet storage practical.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eShelves\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWhile most cabinets come with shelving, there are many additional \u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/catalog/cabinets-kitchen-parts-and-accessories/\"\u003ecabinet parts\u003c/a\u003e for making your life easier.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eShelf organizers for pots, pans, and their matching lids.\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eFloating shelves for your most used items (bowls, mugs, etc.), on eye-level shelves.\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003eRollout shelves as a terrific alternative to traditional shelves, making it easier to access large items.\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003ePulldown shelves for accessing high items, so you don\u0026rsquo;t need a step ladder and can access items safely.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\n\u003cstrong\u003eLazy Susans\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eA Lazy Susan is a swiveling shelf ideal for corner cabinets where accessing the space is awkward and difficult. Perfect for containers, pots and pans, Tupperware, or snacks, a Lazy Susan provides an easier way to reach for kitchen necessities because you can turn the Lazy Susan, bringing the items to the front.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWhen storing containers on Lazy Susans, store lids with them or on the same shelf. These shelves are also great for storing snacks like crackers, canned food, or healthy afterschool treats.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eDrawers\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eDrawer organizers provide a great solution for safely storing utensils, flatware, and dishware. Large drawers are designed to accommodate stacked plates, food storage containers, mixing bowls, and more to keep your countertops free from clutter.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eStore cooking utensils in drawers by type of cooking, for easy access. Drawers close to the stove are perfect for oven gloves or pot-stirring spoons. Island drawers are great for flatware, close to seating or dining areas.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eSpice Racks\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eKeep herbs and spices arranged neatly with a spice rack. Vevano carries a variety of spice rack organizers. Choose a door-mounted spice rack for upper shelves to keep your spice shakers at eye-level. Pick a drawer organizer spice rack to easily customize any drawer and keep your spices within reach. Vevano also carries spice rack base cabinets \u0026ndash; slim 6\u0026rdquo; cabinets with rollout drawers to store spices.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eTrash Can Pull-Outs\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eMaximize your storage space with a pull-out trash can. Many pull-outs also work for recycling and compost bins, or for storing cleaning supplies. A pull-out trash can also free up floor space in your kitchen and keeps trash out of reach from pets and children.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nFAQs About Kitchen Cabinets\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eDo you have a question about your kitchen cabinet remodel? Don\u0026rsquo;t see your question below? Contact our design team at \u003ca href=\"mailto:design@vevano.com\"\u003edesign@vevano.com\u003c/a\u003e to get your questions answered.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eWhat color cabinets make a kitchen look bigger?\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eLight colors are best for making kitchens feel bigger because they reflect light, making rooms feel brighter, airy, and more spacious. White is the most reflective but colors like cream and light greys also reflect more light than darker colors.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eCheck out our \u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/page/white-kitchen-cabinet-collections/\"\u003ewhite kitchen cabinet collections\u003c/a\u003e for a bright kitchen, or our \u003ca href=\"https://vevano.com/page/gray-kitchen-cabinet-collections/\"\u003egrey kitchen cabinet collections\u003c/a\u003e for a slightly warmer kitchen.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eWhat is the best height for kitchen cabinets?\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe standard height for base cabinets is 34 \u0026frac12;\u0026rdquo; (without countertops). The bottom of your wall cabinets should be about 54\u0026rdquo; above the floor. These measurements leave enough space between your wall cabinets and your counter for appliances and cooking space. Wall cabinets themselves are typically between 30\u0026rdquo; and 42\u0026rdquo; high, depending on the design of your kitchen, the cabinet style, and height of your ceiling.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eWhen do you need a cabinet contractor?\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eHire a cabinet contractor when you\u0026rsquo;re ready in start your kitchen remodel. Whether you book an installer before you order cabinets or after, have them contact us at Vevano Pro. We work with your contractor throughout the shipping, assembly, and installation process to ensure your overall satisfaction.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWe recommend hiring a cabinet contractor if any of the following apply to you:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003e\u003cem\u003eYou don\u0026rsquo;t have another person to help you.\u003c/em\u003e Wall cabinets require at least two people to safely and accurately install.\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003e\u003cem\u003eYou\u0026rsquo;re unable to lift more than 20 pounds.\u003c/em\u003e Cabinets are large, so leave the heavy lifting to an expert.\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003e\u003cem\u003eYou have a time constraint.\u003c/em\u003e Installing cabinets prior to a holiday party or selling your home? Professional installers can complete the project quickly.\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli\u003e\u003cem\u003eYour kitchen\u0026rsquo;s floorplan is complicated.\u003c/em\u003e Professionals know how to better handle an uneven floor, non-standard sizing, and electrical or plumbing issues.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eDepending on the size of your kitchen, it usually takes at least 2 to 3 days for a professional to install kitchen cabinets. Give yourself plenty of time if you need your cabinets installed on a deadline.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eHow much does it cost to replace kitchen cabinets?\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe average cost to replace your kitchen cabinets is between $2,000 and $4,000. A general rule is to plan about $100 per linear foot of kitchen. So, if you have a 10 ft wall and another 10 ft wall, that\u0026rsquo;s 20 feet for base cabinets and 20 ft for wall cabinets, or 40 linear feet and $4,000 total.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eVevano carries RTA, or ready to assemble cabinets. With these, the cost of replacing cabinets in a 10x10 kitchen is generally between $2,000 and $3,000 for a 10x10 kitchen. We\u0026rsquo;ll send you detailed instructions for you can assemble cabinets yourself or hire a professional installer to do the work for you.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003ePreassembled cabinets are a bit more expensive, as you are paying for the assembly rather than doing it yourself. They also require more storage space so prepare a section of your home or garage to house the cabinets while you wait to install them.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eCustom cabinets are the most expensive type of cabinetry and can set you back $7,000 to $9,000 (or more) for a 10x10 kitchen. They are best for unique layouts.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eHow much does it cost to install kitchen cabinets?\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eInstalling Your Own Cabinets\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFirst, you need tools: a hammer, ladder, miter saw, drill, stud finder, line level, clamps, and more. The average cost for tools to install kitchen cabinets is about $300 to $700. You can also save money by renting tools from your local hardware shop as well.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003ePros: Save money and learn a new skill.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eCons: Installing your own cabinets without prior experience could result in costly mistakes, injury, or damage to your home.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eHiring a Cabinet Installer\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFor a professional installation, plan on at least $75 per linear foot. Pricing depends on the market in your area, but for a 10x10 kitchen with 40 linear feet, installers charge about $3,000 - $5,000.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003ePros: Trained contractors work quickly and install with more accuracy. Many installers also remove and dispose of your old kitchen cabinets for you.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eCons: Adds significant cost to your renovation.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eHow many cabinets are in a 10x10 kitchen?\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eMost 10x10 kitchens usually have 10-12 cabinets: four to five base cabinets and six to seven wall cabinets. Your unique kitchen may require different quantities or types of cabinets. Some products are more common than others, such as sink base cabinets and corner cabinets for both base and wall. A bridge cabinet for over the refrigerator is also a common design element. Less common are desk, oven, and tall cabinets, since 10x10 kitchens are often too small.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3\u003eWhy are kitchen cabinets expensive?\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eKitchen cabinets are expensive because they\u0026rsquo;re designed to be an integral part of your home for decades. Quality cabinets are built to last up to fifty years or more. Even though it\u0026rsquo;s easy to change your cabinetry, kitchen cabinets are more permanent than ordinary furniture.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eVevano\u0026rsquo;s cabinets are solid, durable, and can add value to your home to recoup some of your original investment. We even carry a few cabinet collections for 10x10 kitchens under $2,000. Contact our design team to receive a kitchen design plan that works with your budget.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e\nExpert Design Services for Your Cabinets\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eReady to replace the cabinets in your kitchen?
